mmodation </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Overall benefit cap</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Bristol’s approach</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have improved links with our internal and external stakeholders in helping those affected by the overall benefit cap.  The most effective way of avoiding the cap for the vast majority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of households affected will be to find employment or explore entitlement to a benefit that exempts the household.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As part of our response, we have two Jobcentre Plus staff co-located with our regeneration team who are ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">badged</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’ as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Bristol City Council</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> emp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">loyees.  They are working closely with staff from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">revenues and b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">enefits service, our landlord service and homelessness to provide employment support.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are undertaking proactive visits and making calls to those affected by the cap to determine how th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ey may deal with the loss of income and what we can do to help from short </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to longer term solutions.  The support offered ranges from referrals to free school meals and nursery places to employment support and training opportunities.  We are also providing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">budgeting and debt advice and making referrals to partners in the third sector where appropriate.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As part of our ongoing approach to awarding Discretionary Housing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ayment, we are granting payments on a shorter term basis and making these conditional on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the household undertaking actions required by the council as part of their action plan.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The issues</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Department for Work and Pensions identified 390 households as affected by the benefit cap in its May scan.  Some of the information shared was inaccura</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">te and included households that should be exempt from the cap.  The cleansed list showed that 352 households would be affected.  As part of our own analysis, we identified around 100 additional households that do not feature on the DWP’s list and therefore</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> may be subject to the cap without any prior support or warning from the DWP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or ourselves</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">52 of the cases identified will have a shortfall that is in excess of 20% of their overall household income</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  The private rented sector and temporary accommodation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are where the benefit cap is being felt keenly, as the rents are traditionally higher in these areas.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There have been reports from some councils of private landlords giving notice to tenants they think may be subject to the benefit cap.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">So far in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Bristol we have been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">advised of four of our affected households that notices have been served.  This is a real concern</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as the private rented sector is one of the only viable options for housing large families (accounting for almost all of the benefit cap c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ases in Bristol).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If households become homeless as a result of the benefit cap and we have a duty to house them, this will be at greater expense than sustaining them within their current tenancies.  Studies suggest that the total cost to government ranges</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> from £24,000 to £30,000 per person annually.  If 50 households affected by the benefit cap become homeless, the annual cost would be £1.5million, almost £400,000 more than the cap is expected to save in Bristol. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Although the government’s intention is to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> incentivise work, many of those who are affected in Bristol suffer from multiple barriers to employment, including lack of English skills, literacy problems, IT skills and large numbers of young children.  We are trying to move these households towards th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e labour market including those who do not need to take part in any work related activity previously (the majority of those affected do not have regular contact with Jobcentre Plus).  It is unlikely that many of these households will find employment before</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the worst effects of the cap are felt.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We welcome the disregarding of Housing Benefit in the calculation of the overall benefit cap for exempt accommodation but this will only apply to a relatively low number of cases where the rent should be safeguarded</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for vulnerable households.  It is also questionable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">why Housing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Benefit is being used </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the vehicle for applying the cap</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> when </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">security of housing i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">priority and Child </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ax </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">redits </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the primary driver for the benefit cap</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in most parts of the country</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The overall cap is a crude mechanism of reducing Housing Benefit entitlement that only affects a small number of households nationally.  Those that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it does</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> affect stand to lose a large amount of their weekly income that has already been determined on th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e basis of need under the current welfare system.  There is also a concern that the increasing cost of living will further squeeze those affected by the cap as it would appear there are no plans to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uprate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the cap amount (if fact, there are current discussi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ons about reducing it further).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Social Sector Size Criteria</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Bristol’s approach</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">generally relied on the landlord’s description of their properties</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> when deciding the number of bedrooms at a property.  This has involved a large data sharing exercis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e with both our landlord services team and the local registered providers.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">All of those affected have received contact from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Bristol City Council</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or their landlord.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Where customers have disputed the number of bedrooms at their property, we have generally </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">referred them back to their landlord.  If the property is owned by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Bristol City Council</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the landlord services team will consider rooms that are less than 50 square feet as being unsuitable for a bedroom.  If a property is reclassified the rent is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">consid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ered as well.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Some of the registered providers have taken this course of action as well.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We undertook an income analysis of tenants affected by under-occupation in order to proactively contact those who may be unable to pay the charge.  Those who appea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">red most financial</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> vulnerable were those single person households on basic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rates of state benefits (£71.70 per week, with an average weekly shortfall of £12 or £21 per week).  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">   </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As is the case with many other authorities, we are monitoring the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overall arrears situation for our tenants and have requested benchmarking information from our registered providers.  We also feed into the core cities comparisons and do so for other welfare reforms.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The issues</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Under-occupation was introduced as a means of freeing up under-occupied properties and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in some respects as a way of incentivising work.  Most of our housing stock is two or three bedroom accommodation, with only a quarter providing one bedroom or studio ac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">commodation.  If all of those affected moved to private rented accommodation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">suitable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for their household size and not subject to a shortfall, the increased cost in Housing Benefit would be £9million per annum.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many of those who have chosen to ‘stay and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> pay’ have not done so with the council seeing a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">30% increase in the number of tenants affected who have rent arrears</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. It is more difficult to see the effects of this policy in the short term as arrears will build much more slowly than in the case of the b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">enefit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cap.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Council Tax Reduction/Support</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Bristol’s approach</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We were one of the few councils</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to fully fund the scheme in year 1 and the only </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">core </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">English city to do so.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This was agreed for this year only and we are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> currently consulting on a scheme for 2014/15.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The decision to fully fund was made </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">before the transitional grant funding was known, chiefly because , </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it was not economical to recover the relatively small debts that would have been created </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from those who</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> were already on low incomes and likely to be impacted by the cumulative impact of other welfare reform changes. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our option</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for 2014/15 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are either to keep the same scheme as year 1 or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">seek to recover 25% of council tax liabilities from all but the most </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘vulnerable’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> working age households (we are currently consulting on who should be protected from a reduction in support).  Although a gross saving of £5million </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">could be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> achieved from this option, the actual saving realised is likely to be in the region of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">£900k after increased collection and administration costs.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The issues</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Councils that have introduced a local scheme that passes a reduction in government funding onto its recipients are reporting an increased demand for customer services and lower coll</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ection rates, inherent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> trying to collect relatively small sums of money from those on low incomes.  There is also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">risk </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the council’s reputation and echoes of the ‘poll tax’ nationally.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This would be another reduction in incomes for those who may </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">already be affected </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by other welfare reforms such as under-occupation or the overall benefit cap.  As an example, a tenant who is under-occupying by one bedroom on basic rates of state </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">benefits and subject to a 25% reduction in support with their council t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ax could lose approximately £17 per week, or almost a quarter of their weekly income.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In writing our scheme for 2014-15, we have attempted to protect groups that may be vulnerable.  There will inevitably be households that do not fit a description of vuln</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">erability through receipt of certain benefits or household makeup and administering another discretionary fund within the scheme would be administratively cumbersome, further reducing any savings that could be made.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The consultation response</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">suggest that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> those</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on low incomes be protected and the basic means tested benefits could be used as a benchmark.  This would lead to cliff edges </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and an increase in the marginal tax rate for those going to work.  This would in turn weaken work incentives, contrary to t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he government’s overall welfare reform agenda and the preferred interaction with Universal Credit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(potentially reducing income from benefits/support faster than it can be replaced by earnings).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Direct payment of housing costs to tenants</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Bristol’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">approach</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are not a direct payments demonstration site but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are following the experiences of those councils with interest.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are considering</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the possibility of council tenants opting out of payments being made directly to their rent accounts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">would be the point at which we would offer referrals for budgeting and money management advice if they want it.  This would support Universal Credit’s objective of financial independence by offering advice before problems arise, with the council having to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">react to a situation then.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As you are aware, we currently administer Local Housing Allowance where the default position is to pay the tenant unless there is a safeguarding reason not to do so or landlord payments are a way of securing or maintaining a ten</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ancy.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The private rented sector plays an important role in homelessness prevention and the ability to safeguard payments for vulnerable tenants </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">helps us to retain access to this housing where there is already a known shortage of social rented sector acc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ommodation.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The issues</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The direct payments demonstration sites have been able to access DWP assistance and funding through the period of the pilot, enabling them to roll out much of the pre-emptive action required to get tenants ready for Universal Cre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dit.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is not clear how much assistance would be available to other councils if they ch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ose to independently embrace this change whilst support for housing costs was still under their direct control (this being preferable to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">payment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">arrangements </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">direct t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">under Universal Credit). </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We would also like further clarification of what the funding structure will look like for the Local Support Services framework.  New activities and services may be funded but as a landlord it would also be in our interest to provide support to our tenants.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This would protect our income and mitigate the social problems associated with loss of income, debt and other problems that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">arise from direct payment.  If this activity was not funded</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, it would be difficult for us to find sufficient re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sources </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">using</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> our current budget for a change implemented by central government.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">What is clear is direct payments may not be appropriate for all tenants that are in scope for it.  We currently retain control over how safeguarding is applied and this is s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ensible as it is the local authority who often carries the risk through homelessness provision, as a landlord and potentially through social services involvement (Bristol is a Unitary Authority) to name a few.  To remove this function and place it with a d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ecision maker who is unlikely to have contact with the tenant is not favourable or workable in our opinion.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To allow councils the discretion over who receives the housing support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">element of any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">payment would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">help to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">retain access </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the private rented sec</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tor.  There is a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">legitimate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fear amongst landlords about direct payments and this could lead to withdrawal from the benefits sub-market.  We anticipate that we will lose an amount of private accommodation and we will face higher costs in securing temporary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and lower quality accommodation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Universal Credit and Housing Costs</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Housing costs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for renters </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have largely been dealt with by councils for over 30 years and there is a wealth of experience and knowledge in this area</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that could be lost if councils do not play a decision making role</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  There is anecdotal evidence to suggest that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the DWP are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">already </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">using authorities in the pathfinder </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">areas </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to help determine rent that is eligible for Universal Credit.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is a concern </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that the administration of housing costs is moving away from the one area of government that will be expected to mitigate the effects when things go wrong.  This has been highlighted in the direct payments section of the document.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Although the housing c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">osts element is not subject to sanction in the same way as the personal allowance is, we are concerned that direct monthly payments in these cases would lead to rent arrears.  This is because funds </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">may</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be used for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">living expenses in the absence of any othe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r available funds.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The expectation of 90 minutes travelling time each way for employment seems unrealistic.  With high speed but often expensive rail links from Bristol to other cities it is possible to get employment elsewhere but the cost could be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">probative, especially if you factor in additional childcare costs.  It is unclear from current information how much common sense and discretion will be exercised by the decision maker in these cases.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Guidance issued to DWP decision makers regarding the nu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mber of effective hours you can seek employment is also a concern, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with one example of how ‘Dave’ fills his day as reading jobs pages in the press for one hour every day.    </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A further 30 minutes a day is dedicated to reviewing and updating his CV.  These l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">evels of activity seem unsustainable for even the most dedicated of jobseekers and could put people who have acted reasonably in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">jobsearch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> at risk of sanction.    </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘Dave’ is also to explore the possibility of being self-employed every day.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Self-emplo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">yment is not a realistic option for many people and given the proposed ‘minimum income floor’ many of those carrying out work to which they would not be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">suitable for will be penalised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> financially if their business did not make the equivalent of minimum wag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e at 35 hours per week</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The zero hours condition associated with housing costs for owner occupiers does not create a work incentive if only a few hours of work are available.  In addition, the conditionality rules could force owner-occupiers to take up em</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ployment that will make them worse off where earnings do not cover the mortgage interest payments.  The additional hardship and debt could lead to the requirement us to intervene in preventing homelessness, an additional cost for the council.    </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Exempt A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weig